Title: Branchial cleft cyst 

A branchial cleft cyst is a lump that develops in the neck or just below the collarbone. It is a type of birth defect.

Subtopic: Causes
Branchial cleft cysts form during development of the embryo. They occur when tissues in the neck and collarbone area (branchial cleft) fail to develop normally.The birth defect may appear as open spaces called cleft sinuses, which may develop on one or both sides of the neck. A branchial cleft cyst may form from fluid drained from a sinus. The cyst or sinus can become infected.

Subtopic: Symptoms
Small pits, lumps, or skin tags at either side of the neck or just below the collarboneFluid drainage from a pit on the neck

Subtopic: Exams and Tests
Your baby's health care provider may be able to diagnose this condition during a physical examination. The following tests may be done: CT scanMRI scanUltrasound

Subtopic: Treatment
Antibiotics will be given if the cyst or sinuses are infected. Surgery is generally done to remove a branchial cyst toÂ prevent complications, such as repeated infections.

Subtopic: Outlook (Prognosis)
Surgery is usually successful, with good results. 

Subtopic: Possible Complications
The cyst or sinuses may become infected.

Subtopic: When to Contact a Medical Professional
Call for an appointment with your health care provider if you notice a small pit, cleft, or lump in the neck or upper shoulder of your infant, especially if fluid drains from this area.

Subtopic: Alternative Names
Cleft sinus